                    <msContents>
                        <summary>This small volume, originally created as a decorative blank book in
                            the mid-17th century, contains delicately sprayed stenciled margins
                            throughout. Its subsequent owners employed it primarily to enter various
                            excerpts of Persian and Eastern Turkish poetry, Arabic quotations, and
                            six ink drawings. At least three hands entered content on its surviving
                            forty-six folios, with two identifiable. The first, one Muḥammad Ḥusayn,
                            wrote primarily in delicate shikastah script and signed an entry in the
                            month of Muḥarram 1065 AH (Nov. 1654 CE). The second, a Muḥammad Taqī
                            al-Rāzī, wrote primarily in nasta‘līq script and signed one entry in the
                            year 1083 AH (1672–1673 CE). </summary>
