                        <decoDesc>
                            <summary>The volume preserves a fragment of the original illuminted
                                header featuring floral scrollwork against a lapis ground. . The The
                                entire volume features various stencilled designs applied mainly to
                                the exterior margins; however, two folios bear additional designs in
                                the central text area. It also contains five ink drawings.</summary>
                            <decoNote type="headpiece"><label>Headpiece</label> Folio <locus
                                    from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus>bears the remnants of an illuminated
                                header.</decoNote>

                            <decoNote type="marginal"><label>Margins:</label> Sprayed stencilled
                                margins in orange and green on most folios feature animals,
                                palmettes, lattices, and floral scrollwork. Folios <locus from="34a"
                                    to="35b">34a–35b</locus> bear stencilled designs reserved for
                                text on the others.</decoNote>
                            <decoNote><label>Drawings:</label> Six hastily rendered late 17th c.
                                style ink drawings found on the following folios:<lb/>
                                <list rend="numbered">
                                    <item> Folios <locus from="8a" to="8a">8a</locus>:
                                            <persName>Majnūn</persName> in the wilderness with
                                        animals.</item>
                                    <item>Folio <locus from="12a" to="12a">12a</locus>: A man fishes
                                        with a net from a stream.</item>
                                    <item>Folio <locus from="22b" to="22b">22b</locus>: A youth
                                        wears a turban in an outdoor landscape.</item>
                                    <item>Folio <locus from="35b" to="35b">35b</locus>: A man
                                        grapples a deer outdoors.</item>
                                    <item>Folio <locus from="40a" to="40a">40a</locus>: A beardless
                                        youth sports a feather sarpīch in his turban.</item>
                                    <item>Folio <locus from="41b" to="41b">41b</locus>: A man on
                                        horseback spears a lion.</item>
                                </list></decoNote>
                        </decoDesc>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding notBefore="1800" notAfter="1900">
                                <p>Probably rebound prior to its arrival in Britain.</p>
                                <p>Resewn at two stations. Covered in semi-limp goatskin
                                        <material>leather</material>. Endpapers of Japanese paper
                                    added during recent conservation treatment. </p>
                                <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                                        <height>80</height>
                                        <width>145</width>
                                        <depth>7</depth>
                                    </dimensions></p>
                                <condition>Handle binding with extreme caution. In fair condition,
                                    albeit with opening to the gutter margins, which remain in
                                    delicate condition.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>Completed as a blank book, probably in <placeName cert="high"
                                type="empire" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/6005089"
                                key="place_6005089">Safavid Empire</placeName>
                            <origDate calendar="#Gregorian" when="1650">ca. 1650 CE</origDate>. </origin>
                        <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired by one Muḥammad Ḥusayn, who signed an
                                entry in the month of Muḥarram 1065 AH (Nov. 1654 CE) and Muḥammad
                                Taqī al-Rāzī, signed another in 1083 AH (1672–1673
                            CE).</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>While the circumstances under which this manuscript arrived
                                in Britain remains unclear, collector <persName role="fmo col dno"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/77114097" key="person_77114097">Robert
                                    Edward Hart (1878-1946)</persName> acquired them from an
                                unidentified source.</p></provenance>
                        <acquisition><p>Bequeathed to the <orgName role="rpo"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/144365237">Blackburn Museum and Art
                                    Gallery</orgName>, <placeName key="place_7027442"
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7027442">Blackburn,
                                    Lancashire</placeName>, after the death of <persName
                                    role="fmo col dno" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/77114097"
                                    key="person_77114097">Robert Edward Hart (1878-1946)</persName>
                                in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1946"
                            >1946</date>.</p></acquisition>
                    </history>
